  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# N-Queens\n\nPlace `n` queens on an `n x n` chessboard so no two queens attack each other. Return every board, using `Q` for queens and `.` for empty cells.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: n = 4\nOutput: [[.Q..,...Q,Q...,..Q.],[..Q.,Q...,...Q,.Q..]]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: n = 1\nOutput: [[Q]]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: n = 3\nOutput: []\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- `1 <= n <= 5` in generated tests.\n- Board order is ignored.",
  "editorial": "Place one queen per row while tracking used columns and diagonals. Backtrack when a placement conflicts.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def solveNQueens(self, n):\n        out = []\n        cols, diag1, diag2 = set(), set(), set()\n        board = [['.'] * n for _ in range(n)]\n        def dfs(row):\n            if row == n:\n                out.append([''.join(line) for line in board])\n                return\n            for col in range(n):\n                if col in cols or row - col in diag1 or row + col in diag2:\n                    continue\n                cols.add(col); diag1.add(row - col); diag2.add(row + col); board[row][col] = 'Q'\n                dfs(row + 1)\n                board[row][col] = '.'; cols.remove(col); diag1.remove(row - col); diag2.remove(row + col)\n        dfs(0)\n        return out\n```",
  "hints": [
    "One queen per row is enough to explore all boards.",
    "Both diagonals can be represented by `row - col` and `row + col`."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def solveNQueens(self, n):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
    "class_name": "Solution",
    "method_name": "solveNQueens"
  },
  "checker": {
